text:
The Ruin (Ukrainian: Руїна) is a historical term that was introduced by the Cossack chronicle writer Samiylo Velychko (1670-1728) for the political situation in Ukraine that covers the period of Ukrainian history of the second half of 17th century. The timeframe of the period varies among historians, for example: 
*  Some publicists such as Nikolay Kostomarov considered it to be between 1663 and 1687 and associating it with the three Moscow-appointed hetmans of the Left-bank Ukraine (Briukhovetsky, Mnohohrishny, and Samoylovych); 
*  Other historians interpret it between 1660 and 1687 from the Chudniv Treaty that led to division among the Cossack community; 
*  Borys Krupnytsky considered the timeframe 1657-1687 from the death of hetman Bohdan Khmelnitsky in 1657, particularly the Pushkar-Barabash Mutiny, and until ascension of hetman Ivan Mazepa in 1687. This period is characterised by continuous strife, civil war, and foreign intervention of Ukraine's neighbours. The Ukrainian saying of the time: "Від Богдана до Івана не було гетьмана" (From Bohdan to Ivan there was no hetman [in between]) — accurately summarises the chaotic events of this period.
